question:
Refer to Example 5.1 and the outcome $x$ of a $\$ 5$ wager in craps. We found the sampling distributions of the sample mean $\bar{x}$ and the sample median $m$ for random samples of $n=3$ dice rolls from a population defined by the following probability distribution:

\begin{tabular}{l|ccc}
\hline $\boldsymbol{x}$ & -5 & 0 & 5 \\
\hline $\boldsymbol{p}(\boldsymbol{x})$ & $\frac{1}{9}$ & $\frac{6}{9}$ & $\frac{2}{9}$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

The sampling distributions of $\bar{x}$ and $m$ were found to be as follows:

\begin{tabular}{l|ccccccc}
\hline $\boldsymbol{x}$ & -5 & -3.33 & -1.67 & 0 & 1.67 & 3.33 & 5 \\
\hline $\boldsymbol{p}(\overline{\boldsymbol{x}})$ & $\frac{1}{729}$ & $\frac{18}{729}$ & $\frac{114}{729}$ & $\frac{288}{729}$ & $\frac{228}{729}$ & $\frac{72}{729}$ & $\frac{8}{729}$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}

\begin{tabular}{l|ccc}
\hline $\boldsymbol{m}$ & -5 & 0 & 5 \\
\hline $\boldsymbol{p}(\boldsymbol{m})$ & $\frac{25}{729}$ & $\frac{612}{729}$ & $\frac{92}{729}$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
a. Show that $\bar{x}$ is an unbiased estimator of $\mu$ in this situation.
b. Show that $m$ is a biased estimator of $\mu$ in this situation.
